{"type":"message","id":"dd02181b","parentId":"6d093dc4","timestamp":"2026-06-15T02:42:36.869Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Good, the init_skill.py script exists. Let me now:\n\n1. Use `init_skill.py` to create the skill skeleton\n2. Write the keepalive and login scripts\n3. Write the SKILL.md\n4. Then set up the cron jobs\n\nBut first, I should ask the user about where the skill should be saved. Actually, looking at the skill-creator doc, it says:\n\n```bash\nscripts/init_skill.py <skill-name> --path <output-directory>\n```\n\nI can run this to create the skeleton. Let me do it.\n\nActually, wait - I should think about where to put the skill. The user's existing skills are in `~/.openclaw/plugin-skills/`. But the skill-creator seems designed for creating skills that get packaged. Let me think about this differently.\n\nFor a skill to be used by OpenClaw, it needs to be in a directory that's in the `skills.load.extraDirs` config. Currently that's `~/.openclaw/plugin-skills`. So I should create it there.\n\nLet me plan:\n\n1. Run `init_skill.py` to initialize the skill skeleton\n2. Customize SKILL.md\n3. Write scripts/tapd_login.mjs - for initial login to get cookies\n4. Write scripts/tapd_keepalive.mjs - for daily cookie keepalive\n5. Write references/tapd-login.md - reference file for login flows\n6. Set up cron jobs for the keepalive\n\nActually, let me think about this... The problem was the previous cron referenced a script under `workspace/scripts/` that didn't exist. For the new setup, I should either:\n\na) Put the scripts inside the skill directory (plugin-skills/tapd-cookie-keepalive/scripts/)\nb) Put the scripts directly in workspace/scripts/\n\nSince we're making this a skill, option (a) makes more sense. The cron can reference the skill's script path.\n\nLet me also check what the current plugin-skills directory structure looks like for reference.","thinkingSignature":"reasoning_content"},{"type":"toolCall","id"