{"type":"custom_message","customType":"openclaw.runtime-context","content":"Conversation info (untrusted metadata):\n```json\n{\n  \"chat_id\": \"user:ou_6509d346e8d50ef882f89c436e6c977f\",\n  \"message_id\": \"om_x100b6dcdf1e02080b3cf3d1a89eaeac\",\n  \"sender_id\": \"ou_6509d346e8d50ef882f89c436e6c977f\",\n  \"sender\": \"Yousan(叶枝君)\",\n  \"timestamp\": \"Mon 2026-06-15 14:30 GMT+8\"\n}\n```\n\nSender (untrusted metadata):\n```json\n{\n  \"label\": \"Yousan(叶枝君) (ou_6509d346e8d50ef882f89c436e6c977f)\",\n  \"id\": \"ou_6509d346e8d50ef882f89c436e6c977f\",\n  \"name\": \"Yousan(叶枝君)\"\n}\n```","display":false,"details":{"source":"openclaw-runtime-context"},"id":"113c1e2c","parentId":"e2356d5d","timestamp":"2026-06-15T06:30:15.560Z"}
{"type":"message","id":"7a2e3e97","parentId":"113c1e2c","timestamp":"2026-06-15T06:30:40.227Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"The user doesn't want a loop/polling approach. They want real-time, interactive conversation with Cursor. This means I need to find a way to have a persistent, bidirectional communication channel with Cursor's agent.\n\nThe key challenge is that `cursor agent` doesn't work in a non-interactive context (it exits immediately when stdin is not a real TTY). But I verified that `node-pty` works on this system. The issue is specifically `cursor agent` detecting it's not in a proper terminal.\n\nLet me think about other approaches:\n\n1. **`cursor --add-mcp <json>`** - Register an MCP server. This adds a tool to Cursor. If I register a server that provides a tool like `get_instruction_from_openclaw`, then when the user talks to Cursor agent, Cursor can call my MCP tool to fetch the instruction. But this is Cursor→me, not me→Cursor.\n\n2. **Custom MCP server** - I run an MCP server that provides tools that Cursor can call. The user asks Cursor \"check if there's a task from OpenClaw\", Cursor calls my MCP tool.\n\n3. **Reverse approach** - Instead of me pushing to Cursor, what if Cursor pulls from me? I create a local HTTP server, register it as an MCP tool, and Cursor can query it.\n\n4. **WebSocket/Event approach** - What if I set up a WebSocket connection that Cursor can connect to?\n\nActually, let me reconsider the PTY approach. The issue is `cursor agent` specifically. But what about just running `cmd.exe` in the PTY and then the user interacts with it? No, that doesn't make sense.\n\nWait - let me reconsider. The user said \"实时对话\" (real-time conversation). Maybe what they want is:\n- I relay messages between Feishu and Cursor in real-time\n- Like a chat bridge: Feishu ↔ me ↔ Cursor\n\nFor this, I need a persistent bidirectional connection. The MCP approach is actually bidirectional if I design it right:\n1. I run an MCP server locally\n2. It has a tool like `pending_instruction` that Cursor's agent can call\n3. When user sends message from phone, I write it to a pending buffer\n4. When Cursor's agent calls `pending_instruction`, it gets the message and executes it\n5. The agent calls another tool `submit_result` to send the result back\n6. I read the result and forward it back to the user\n\nBut this is still \"pull-based\" (Cursor pulls from me), not \"push-based\" (I push to Cursor).\n\nFor real push-based communication, let me think about what's possible:\n\n**Option 1: MCP with notification**\n- Cursor registers me as an MCP server with tools\n- I have a `notify` tool that Cursor polls with notifications\n- But this is still polling...\n\n**Option 2: Background Cursor Agent via proper TTY**\n- The cursor agent exits because there's no real TTY\n- What if I create a pseudo-console using Windows API?\n\n**Option 3: Windows ConPTY API**\n- Windows 10+ has ConPTY (pseudo console) API\n- I can use `node-pty` with a proper terminal\n- The issue was that `cursor agent` specifically checks for interactivity\n- But maybe it checks the stdin handle type, and a PTY might work\n\nLet me test this more carefully. In my earlier test, I used `pty.spawn('cmd.exe', ['/c', 'cursor', 'agent'])`. Maybe I should try spawning `cursor.cmd` directly (not through cmd.exe).\n\nActually wait - I already tried that:\n```js\npty.spawn('C:\\\\...\\\\cursor.cmd', ['agent'], {...})\n```\nAnd it immediately exited with code 0 and produced 0 output.\n\nBut `pty.spawn('cmd.exe', ['/c', 'where cursor'], {...})` worked fine and produced output.\n\nSo the issue is specifically with `cursor agent`. Let me check what happens if I run `cursor agent` from a regular Command Prompt vs from PowerShell with proper stdin.\n\nActually, let me try a completely different approach. What if I use `cmd.exe /k` or `start` to keep the window open?\n\nOr, what if the issue is that `cursor agent` checks `process.stdout.isTTY`? In a PTY, stdout IS a TTY. Let me test more carefully.\n\nLet me try pty.spawn with the cursor.cmd directly and see if there's any output that I missed.","thinkingSignature":"reasoning_content"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_00_Y4NXAgIZ9sDnji2S6QSL0187","name":"write","arguments":{"content":"const pty = require('node-pty');\n\n// Test 1: cmd.exe normal\nconsole.log('=== Test 1: cmd.exe with echo ===');\nconst p1 = pty.spawn('cmd.exe', ['/c', 'echo PTY_WORKS && dir /b'], {\n  name: 'xterm-256color', cols: 120, rows: 40,\n  cwd: 'C:\\\\Users\\\\yyzypublic\\\\.openclaw\\\\workspace',\n  env: process.env\n});\np1.onData(d => process.stdout.write('[p1] ' + d.replace(/\\u001b\\[.*?[a-zA-Z]/g, '')));\np1.onExit(() => {});\n\n// Test 2: cursor --version\nsetTimeout(() => {\n  console.log('\\n=== Test 2: cursor --version ===');\n  const p2 = pty.spawn('cmd.exe', ['/c', 'cursor', '--version'], {\n    name: 'xterm-256color', cols: 120, rows: 40,\n    cwd: 'C:\\\\Users\\\\yyzypublic\\\\.openclaw\\\\workspace',\n    env: process.env\n  });\n  p2.onData(d => process.stdout.write('[p2] ' + d.replace(/\\u001b\\[.*?[a-zA-Z]/g, '')));\n  p2.onExit(() => {});\n}, 2000);\n\n// Test 3: cursor agent (key test!)\nsetTimeout(() => {\n  console.log('\\n=== Test 3: cursor agent ===');\n  let out = '';\n  const p3 = pty.spawn('cmd.exe', [], {\n    name: 'xterm-256color', cols: 120, rows: 40,\n    cwd: 'C:\\\\Users\\\\yyzypublic\\\\.openclaw\\\\workspace',\n    env: process.env\n  });\n  p3.onData(d => {\n    out += d;\n    const clean = d.replace(/\\u001b\\[.*?[a-zA-Z]/g, '').replace(/[\\x00-\\x08\\x0b\\x0c\\x0e-\\x1f]/g, '');\n    if (clean.trim()) process.stdout.write('[p3] ' + clean);\n  });\n  p3.onExit(({exitCode}) => {\n    console.log(`\\n[p3] EXIT code=${exitCode}, outputLen=${out.length}`);\n  });\n\n  // Send cursor agent command\n  setTimeout(() => {\n    console.log('\\n[p3] SENDING: cursor agent\\n');\n    p3.write('cursor agent\\n');\n  }, 1000);\n\n  // After a few seconds, send a command to the agent\n  setTimeout(() => {\n    console.log('\\n[p3] SENDING: echo hello from cursor bridge\\n');\n    p3.write('echo hello from cursor bridge\\n');\n  }, 8000);\n\n  // Finish\n  setTimeout(() => {\n    console.log(`\\n[p3 FINAL OUTPUT LEN: ${out.length}]`);\n    const clean = out.replace(/\\u001b\\[.*?[a-zA-Z]/g, '').replace(/[\\x00-\\x08\\x0b\\x0c\\x0e-\\x1f\\x7f-\\x9f]/g, '');\n    console.log('[p3 RAW]:', clean.substring(0, 3000));\n    process.exit(0);\n  }, 15000);\n}, 4000);\n","path":"C:\\Users\\yyzypublic\\.openclaw\\workspace\\test_pty2.cjs"}}],"api":"openai-completions","provider":"deepseek","model":"deepseek-v4-flash","usage":{"input":161815,"output":1803,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":163618,"cost":{"input":0.0226541,"output":0.00050484,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0.02315894}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1781505015560,"responseId":"b335a028-8989-4680-9ac0-947c00407407"}}
