{"type":"message","id":"c2b4b31a","parentId":"f69765ee","timestamp":"2026-06-15T06:31:17.865Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Interesting! Tests 1 and 2 worked fine. Test 3 ran `cmd.exe` in PTY, then sent `cursor agent` command, but... cursor agent didn't produce any visible output. It ran silently. The output just shows the typed command but no agent response.\n\nWait, looking more carefully at the output:\n- `cursor agent` was typed\n- `echo hello from cursor bridge` was typed\n- No agent output between them\n\nThis means `cursor agent` ran and exited without doing anything visible. It detected it's a cmd.exe session (not a proper terminal) and didn't start.\n\nLet me try a different approach. Instead of running `cursor agent` through cmd.exe, let me try running the Electron process directly with the right flags.\n\nActually, looking at cursor.cmd:\n```\n@echo off\nsetlocal\nset VSCODE_DEV=\nset ELECTRON_RUN_AS_NODE=1\n\"%~dp0..\\..\\..\\Cursor.exe\" \"%~dp0..\\out\\cli.js\" %*\n```\n\nIt sets `ELECTRON_RUN_AS_NODE=1` and runs `Cursor.exe` with `cli.js`. The `agent` command is passed as an argument to cli.js.\n\nLet me try running it directly via the PTY with the ELECTRON_RUN_AS_NODE flag. Actually, I already tried `pty.spawn('cursor.cmd', ['agent'])`. Let me try running the direct Electron command.\n\nBut wait - maybe the issue is that `cursor agent` on Windows requires a GUI (it opens a terminal window). In a PTY, there's no GUI window to open.\n\nLet me think about this differently. Instead of fighting with cursor agent, what if I use a completely different approach?\n\n**Approach: Use Cursor's built-in HTTP/WebSocket MCP server protocol**\n\nLooking at the `--add-mcp` option:\n```\n--add-mcp <json>  Adds a Model Context Protocol server definition to the user profile\n```\n\nThis adds an MCP server to Cursor. The MCP server can provide tools that Cursor's agent can call. But this is Cursor→me, not me→Cursor.\n\nBUT - what if I combine this with a technique where:\n1. I run an MCP server\n2. The MCP server has a tool `get_pending_task` that Cursor can call\n3. The user tells Cursor agent to wait for and check my MCP tool\n4. I push instructions to the MCP server's pending buffer\n\nThis is essentially the same as file-pulling but through MCP.\n\n**Approach: Custom MCP server that bridges bidirectionally**\n\nActually, let me think about this even more differently. What if I:\n\n1. Create a local WebSocket server\n2. Open a ConPTY terminal window (real window) that runs `cursor agent`\n3. When the user sends a message, I:\n   - Send it through the WebSocket to a helper script\n   - The helper script injects the keystroke into the Cursor Agent window\n   - Reads the response from the window\n\nThis is essentially GUI automation. It's complex but possible.\n\nActually, the SIMPLEST approach that gives real-time communication:\n\n**Approach: Launch cursor agent in a real visible terminal window**\n\nI can use `Start-Process` to launch a new terminal window running `cursor agent`. Then I can:\n- Use the terminal's stdin/stdout for communication\n- Or use SendKeys/similar for GUI automation\n\nBut this still has the problem that I can't easily communicate with a separate process's terminal.\n\nWait, I just had another idea. What about using named pipes or the Windows Console API?\n\n**Best Approach: SSH-like reverse tunnel**\n\n1. I can start `cursor agent` in a real terminal window on the user's desktop\n2. Use PowerShell Remoting or a named pipe to communicate with it\n3. Forward messages bidirectionally\n\nActually, the SIMPLEST working approach:\n\n**Use ConPTY (Windows Pseudo Console) via `node-pty` with the right settings**\n\nThe issue might be that `cursor agent` specifically needs to detect a Windows console. Let me check if `node-pty` creates a proper Windows console.\n\nActually, I just realized something. When `cursor agent` is run:\n1. `ELECTRON_RUN_AS_NODE=1` makes it run as a Node.js process\n2. It reads `cli.js` as the entry point\n3. `cli.js` handles the `agent` subcommand\n\nThe `agent` subcommand likely spawns the Cursor Agent interface, which requires:\n- A real terminal (not just pipe/PTY)\n- Possibly GUI elements\n\nLet me try a completely different tactic: **send instructions to Cursor via its running instance's API**.\n\nCursor, like VS Code, might have a local HTTP server or IPC channel that extensions use. If I can find the pipe/socket, I can send commands to it.\n\nLet me check if Cursor has a VS Code-compatible extension host or API.","thinkingSignature":"reasoning_content"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_00_xu3VRx8EERVj0dwVa6bu1322","name":"exec","arguments":{"command":"# 看看 Cursor 是否有 IPC 通信端口\nGet-Process -Name \"Cursor\" -ErrorAction SilentlyContinue | Select-Object Id, ProcessName, StartTime\n\nWrite-Output \"=== Checking IPC pipes ===\"\n# VS Code uses named pipes like \\\\.\\pipe\\vscode-ipc-<guid>\nGet-ChildItem \"\\\\.\\pipe\\\" -ErrorAction SilentlyContinue | Where-Object { $_.Name -match \"cursor|vscode\" } | Select-Object Name\n\nWrite-Output \"=== Cursor debug/extension ports ===\"\nnetstat -ano 2>$null | Select-String \"18789|18790|18791\" | Select-Object -First 5","timeout":10}}],"api":"openai-completions","provider":"deepseek","model":"deepseek-v4-flash","usage":{"input":649,"output":1276,"cacheRead":163840,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":165765,"cost":{"input":0.00009086000000000001,"output":0.00035728,"cacheRead":0.0045875199999999994,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0.005035659999999999}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1781505063375,"responseId":"6b67fca4-220a-43dd-a084-c2ffbdc83eaa"}}
