{"type":"custom_message","customType":"openclaw.runtime-context","content":"Conversation info (untrusted metadata):\n```json\n{\n  \"chat_id\": \"user:ou_6509d346e8d50ef882f89c436e6c977f\",\n  \"message_id\": \"om_x100b6dce2754ec80b14bee28bfd3cac\",\n  \"sender_id\": \"ou_6509d346e8d50ef882f89c436e6c977f\",\n  \"sender\": \"Yousan(叶枝君)\",\n  \"timestamp\": \"Mon 2026-06-15 15:15 GMT+8\"\n}\n```\n\nSender (untrusted metadata):\n```json\n{\n  \"label\": \"Yousan(叶枝君) (ou_6509d346e8d50ef882f89c436e6c977f)\",\n  \"id\": \"ou_6509d346e8d50ef882f89c436e6c977f\",\n  \"name\": \"Yousan(叶枝君)\"\n}\n```","display":false,"details":{"source":"openclaw-runtime-context"},"id":"5ea9646b","parentId":"3c12a1fe","timestamp":"2026-06-15T07:15:41.965Z"}
{"type":"message","id":"caf382ac","parentId":"5ea9646b","timestamp":"2026-06-15T07:16:05.945Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"The user is saying the MCP approach isn't what they want - they don't want to have to manually go to Cursor and ask it to check for tasks. They want me to directly interact with Cursor via the CLI without their manual intervention.\n\nBut earlier I tried `cursor agent` and it doesn't work in a headless/background context - it exits immediately when not in a real interactive terminal.\n\nHowever, I DID find that `cursor agent` works when started in a **real Windows terminal window** via `Start-Process cmd -ArgumentList '/k cursor agent'`. The issue was that I couldn't communicate with it from OpenClaw because:\n1. `SendKeys` was blocked (access denied)\n2. But I was able to detect the window (HWND: 267130, titled \"● agent - Cursor\")\n\nLet me reconsider the approach. The user says they have Cursor CLI installed. The previous issues were:\n1. `cursor agent` exits in non-interactive mode\n2. But it works in a real terminal window\n\nWait - the user says \"我安装了Cursor cli\" - but cursor CLI was already installed (`cursor --version` showed 3.7.19). Maybe they mean they installed something specific for CLI integration?\n\nActually, let me re-read: \"功能不对, 不应该还需要我去Cursor操作,我安装了Cursor cli, 再试试通过cli跟Cursor交互\"\n\nThey're saying:\n1. The feature is wrong - they shouldn't need to manually go to Cursor\n2. They have Cursor CLI installed\n3. Try again to interact with Cursor through CLI\n\nSo they want me to find a way to send instructions to Cursor through the CLI that WORKS automatically.\n\nLet me think about what options I have:\n\n1. **`cursor agent` with a real window + Windows API communication** - Start cursor agent in a real cmd window, then use Windows API to write to its console. The earlier `SetForegroundWindow` approach partially worked but `SendKeys` was blocked (access denied).\n\n2. **Write to the console buffer directly** - Use `kernel32!WriteConsoleInput` or `kernel32!AttachConsole` to write to the agent's console.\n\n3. **`cursor` CLI with `--add-mcp` that enables push** - Instead of MCP pull (Cursor calls me), what if I set up the MCP server so that when Cursor connects, I can push notifications?\n\n4. **Pipe-based approach with proper TTY** - Use a named pipe or similar to create a proper terminal environment.\n\nActually, let me re-examine option 2 more carefully. I opened `cursor agent` in a real window before. What if I:\n1. Start cursor agent with a specific title/name\n2. Use `kernel32!AttachConsole` to attach to its console\n3. Write input to the console buffer\n4. Read output from the console buffer\n\nThe `AttachConsole` approach earlier had issues with the C# struct definitions. Let me try using PowerShell's built-in capabilities or a simpler method.\n\nActually, wait. Let me reconsider the `cursor --add-mcp` approach. What if instead of the user asking Cursor to check for tasks, I make it so that:\n1. I run an MCP server\n2. The MCP server registers a custom tool\n3. When Cursor connects to the MCP server, the server can NOTIFY Cursor (MCP supports notifications)\n4. Or, Cursor's agent automatically polls the MCP tools\n\nActually, MCP protocol supports `notifications` that the server can send to the client. If I can send a notification to Cursor when a new task arrives...\n\nBut I don't think the current MCP protocol implementation in Cursor supports server-initiated notifications triggering agent actions.\n\nLet me try the AttachConsole approach more carefully. Let me write a Node.js script that:\n1. Starts `cursor agent` in a new cmd window (which works, we proved this)\n2. Uses `node-pty` or Windows native console API to communicate with it\n\nActually wait - I should try a completely different approach. What about using the `node-pty` module to create a PTY that cursor agent thinks is a real terminal? The issue earlier was that `cursor agent` checks for a real Windows console.\n\nBut what if I configure the PTY differently? In Windows, `node-pty` uses ConPTY (Windows Pseudo Console). Maybe I need to set specific environment variables or use specific terminal emulation.\n\nLet me test one more thing: what if I run `cursor agent` through `ConPTY` with the right initialization? The `node-pty` library on Windows should create a proper pseudo console.\n\nActually, earlier when I ran the test_pty3.cjs, Test C showed:\n```\n[C] Starting cursor agent...\n[C] cursor agent\n```\nThe command was typed but produced no output. The agent exited without doing anything.\n\nWhat if the issue is that `cursor agent` requires a GUI desktop to be present? Like it tries to open a window?\n\nLet me try a different tactic - use `cmd.exe /k` to keep the cursor agent running in an interactive state, then use the PTY to interact with it.\n\nWait, actually I already tried `cmd.exe` with cmd.exe interactive and then sent `cursor agent`. The agent started but produced no output in the PTY. But when I ran it via `Start-Process cmd -ArgumentList '/k cursor agent'`, it opened a REAL window and WORKED (I saw \"● agent - Cursor\" in the taskbar).\n\nSo the issue is clear: `cursor agent` checks if it has a REAL window (window handle/HWND) and only starts when it has one. ConPTY/PTY doesn't create a real window, it creates a virtual console.\n\nThe solution:\n1. Open a real but HIDDEN window running `cursor agent`\n2. Use Windows API to write to its console\n\nLet me try this approach. I'll create a visible but minimized window, then write to its console via API.\n\nActually, let me try something simpler first. What if I use `node-pty` to spawn `cmd.exe` with `/k` flag, which keeps cmd running, and then inside that cmd session run `cursor agent`? The key question is whether cmd.exe's console in a PTY has a real window. It probably doesn't.\n\nOK, different approach entirely. What about writing to the cursor agent process via a Windows Console API script (in Node.js with native bindings)?\n\nLet me try yet another angle: **named pipe communication**. What if cursor agent can be configured to read from a named pipe instead of stdin?\n\nActually, let me look at this from a simpler angle. The `cursor` CLI is based on VS Code CLI. VS Code CLI supports `--command` to execute commands in a running instance. Let me check if cursor supports IPC commands to its running instance.","thinkingSignature":"reasoning_content"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_00_tgEkKFSKq8gbf2VVx42U7360","name":"exec","arguments":{"command":"# Check if Cursor supports VS Code-style --command or IPC\n# VS Code has a socket/pipe for IPC\n\n# Look for Cursor's running process details\nGet-Process -Name \"Cursor\" -ErrorAction SilentlyContinue | Select-Object Id, MainWindowTitle, StartTime |\n    Where-Object { $_.StartTime -gt (Get-Date).AddHours(-1) }\n\n# Check for IPC pipes\n$pipes = [System.IO.Directory]::GetFiles(\"\\\\.\\\\pipe\\\\\") | Where-Object { $_ -match \"cursor|vscode|ms-vscode\" }\nWrite-Output \"IPC Pipes: $pipes\"\n\n# Check if there's a cursor socket/lock file\nGet-ChildItem \"$env:APPDATA\\Cursor\" -Name -Filter \"*.sock\" -ErrorAction SilentlyContinue\nGet-ChildItem \"$env:APPDATA\\Cursor\" -Name -Filter \"*.pid\" -ErrorAction SilentlyContinue\nGet-ChildItem \"$env:APPDATA\\Cursor\" -Name -Filter \"*lock*\" -ErrorAction SilentlyContinue","timeout":10}}],"api":"openai-completions","provider":"deepseek","model":"deepseek-v4-flash","usage":{"input":6560,"output":1758,"cacheRead":207104,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":215422,"cost":{"input":0.0009184000000000001,"output":0.00049224,"cacheRead":0.005798912,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0.007209552}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1781507741965,"responseId":"b8746828-5626-410b-afa7-4b2393d8f1fa"}}
{"type":"message","id":"02b1a188","parentId":"caf382ac","timestamp":"2026-06-15T07:16:06.335Z","message":{"role":"toolResult","toolCallId":"call_00_tgEkKFSKq8gbf2VVx42U7360","toolName":"exec","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Id MainWindowTitle StartTime         \r\n   -- --------------- ---------         \r\n10872                 2026/6/15 14:48:13\r\n11320                 2026/6/15 14:48:52\r\n12972 Cursor Agents   2026/6/15 14:48:08\r\n16760                 2026/6/15 14:48:10\r\n17028                 2026/6/15 14:48:11\r\n17068                 2026/6/15 14:48:11\r\n18512                 2026/6/15 14:48:16\r\n18712                 2026/6/15 14:48:15\r\n18996                 2026/6/15 14:48:16\r\n19128                 2026/6/15 14:48:16\r\n20356                 2026/6/15 14:48:19\r\nIPC Pipes: \\\\.\\\\pipe\\\\vscode-git-c4447d64a5-sock \\\\.\\\\pipe\\\\vscode-ipc-0906bd42-ad7b-4eb2-8498-67992584966e-sock \\\\.\\\\pipe\\\\vscode-git-9cce4dec6c-sock\r\ncode.lock"}],"details":{"status":"completed","exitCode":0,"durationMs":294,"aggregated":"Id MainWindowTitle StartTime         \r\n   -- --------------- ---------         \r\n10872                 2026/6/15 14:48:13\r\n11320                 2026/6/15 14:48:52\r\n12972 Cursor Agents   2026/6/15 14:48:08\r\n16760                 2026/6/15 14:48:10\r\n17028                 2026/6/15 14:48:11\r\n17068                 2026/6/15 14:48:11\r\n18512                 2026/6/15 14:48:16\r\n18712                 2026/6/15 14:48:15\r\n18996                 2026/6/15 14:48:16\r\n19128                 2026/6/15 14:48:16\r\n20356                 2026/6/15 14:48:19\r\nIPC Pipes: \\\\.\\\\pipe\\\\vscode-git-c4447d64a5-sock \\\\.\\\\pipe\\\\vscode-ipc-0906bd42-ad7b-4eb2-8498-67992584966e-sock \\\\.\\\\pipe\\\\vscode-git-9cce4dec6c-sock\r\ncode.lock","cwd":"C:\\Users\\yyzypublic\\.openclaw\\workspace"},"isError":false,"timestamp":1781507766335}}
{"type":"message","id":"feba4ffb","parentId":"02b1a188","timestamp":"2026-06-15T07:16:13.092Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Interesting! There are running Cursor processes and IPC pipes!\n\nI can see:\n- `Cursor Agents` window (PID 12972) - this is the Cursor agent window!\n- `vscode-ipc-0906bd42-ad7b-4eb2-8498-67992584966e-sock` - This is an IPC socket!\n- `vscode-git-*` - Git extension sockets\n- `code.lock` - Lock file\n\nVS Code (and Cursor) uses a named pipe for IPC communication with running instances. I can use this pipe to send commands to the running Cursor instance!\n\nThe IPC pipe for VS Code/Cursor follows the VS Code `--command` protocol. I can send JSON messages to the pipe to execute commands in the running Cursor instance.\n\nLet me check if I can use the VS Code window management protocol to:\n1. Open the agent\n2. Send a message to the agent\n3. Get the result\n\nVS Code's IPC protocol uses a specific message format. The pipe path is `\\\\.\\pipe\\vscode-ipc-<uuid>-sock`. I can try to send commands to it.\n\nLet me write a Node.js script that connects to this pipe and sends commands.","thinkingSignature":"reasoning_content"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_00_7zd1dmwp3RX0LzQndt4q7272","name":"exec","arguments":{"command":"# 检查 Cursor 是否正在运行（寻找主窗口）\n$mainProc = Get-Process -Name \"Cursor\" -ErrorAction SilentlyContinue | Where-Object { $_.MainWindowTitle -ne \"\" -and $_.MainWindowTitle -ne \"Cursor Agents\" }\nWrite-Output \"Cursor main window:\"\n$mainProc | Select-Object Id, @{N='Title';E={$_.MainWindowTitle}} | Format-Table\n\nWrite-Output \"`nIPC pipe details:\"\nGet-ChildItem \"\\\\.\\pipe\\\" -ErrorAction SilentlyContinue | Where-Object { $_.Name -match \"vscode-ipc\" } | ForEach-Object {\n    Write-Output \"  $_\"\n}","timeout":10}}],"api":"openai-completions","provider":"deepseek","model":"deepseek-v4-flash","usage":{"input":427,"output":479,"cacheRead":215296,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":216202,"cost":{"input":0.00005978000000000001,"output":0.00013412,"cacheRead":0.006028288,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0.006222188}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1781507766340,"responseId":"3c916b9c-7b6c-4b62-afc4-5c688c9b8e97"}}
{"type":"message","id":"28be2fa6","parentId":"feba4ffb","timestamp":"2026-06-15T07:16:13.369Z","message":{"role":"toolResult","toolCallId":"call_00_7zd1dmwp3RX0LzQndt4q7272","toolName":"exec","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Cursor main window:\r\n\nIPC pipe details:\r\n  vscode-ipc-0906bd42-ad7b-4eb2-8498-67992584966e-sock"}],"details":{"status":"completed","exitCode":0,"durationMs":260,"aggregated":"Cursor main window:\r\n\nIPC pipe details:\r\n  vscode-ipc-0906bd42-ad7b-4eb2-8498-67992584966e-sock","cwd":"C:\\Users\\yyzypublic\\.openclaw\\workspace"},"isError":false,"timestamp":1781507773369}}
{"type":"message","id":"3083c7ec","parentId":"28be2fa6","timestamp":"2026-06-15T07:16:25.086Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"There's no main Cursor window (main window title is empty), but the IPC pipe exists. However, there is a `Cursor Agents` window with PID 12972.\n\nThe IPC pipe `vscode-ipc-0906bd42-ad7b-4eb2-8498-67992584966e-sock` is available. Let me write a Node.js script that connects to this IPC socket and sends VS Code-compatible IPC messages to open commands in the running Cursor instance.\n\nVS Code's IPC protocol:\n- Uses JSON-RPC-like messages\n- Messages are sent as length-prefixed JSON strings\n- Commands can be invoked via the `workspace` or `window` services\n\nBut this is quite complex. Let me think of a simpler approach.\n\nActually, the simplest approach that would work reliably:\n\n1. **Start `cursor agent` in a real but hidden window** \n2. **Use the Windows Console API to read/write to it**\n\nLet me write a Node.js script that:\n1. Uses `node-windows` or directly `child_process` to start cmd.exe with `/k cursor agent` in a hidden window\n2. Then uses a C++ addon or PowerShell script to attach to that console and send commands\n\nActually, wait. Let me try something I haven't tried yet: **using PowerShell Remoting or `Start-Transcript` to capture the console output**.\n\nOr better yet, let me try the `conin$.exe` / `conout$.exe` approach - these are special Windows console devices that allow reading/writing console input/output from another process.\n\nOn Windows, you can open `CONIN$` and `CONOUT$` to access the console of a process. But this only works for the current console.\n\nLet me try a completely different approach. What if I:\n1. Create a \"bridge\" PowerShell script\n2. The script starts cursor agent in a new window\n3. Uses `Add-Type` with C# code to attach to the console and communicate\n4. Returns results via a temp file\n\nLet me write this in a clean way.","thinkingSignature":"reasoning_content"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_00_eCFCrGN8AhKrzjiyg7IT0449","name":"exec","arguments":{"command":"# Let's check if cursor agent window is still open\n$agentWins = @()\nAdd-Type -AssemblyName System.Windows.Forms\n$allWindows = [System.Windows.Forms.Application]::OpenForms\n\n# Use Win32 API to find windows\n$sig = @'\n[DllImport(\"user32.dll\")]\npublic static extern IntPtr FindWindow(string lpClassName, string lpWindowName);\n[DllImport(\"user32.dll\", CharSet = CharSet.Auto)]\npublic static extern int GetWindowText(IntPtr hWnd, System.Text.StringBuilder text, int count);\n[DllImport(\"user32.dll\")]\npublic static extern int GetWindowTextLength(IntPtr hWnd);\n'@\n$win32 = Add-Type -MemberDefinition $sig -Name \"Win32Find\" -Namespace Win32 -PassThru\n\n$hwnd = $win32::FindWindow($null, \"● agent - Cursor\")\nif ($hwnd -ne [IntPtr]::Zero) {\n    $len = $win32::GetWindowTextLength($hwnd)\n    $sb = New-Object System.Text.StringBuilder ($len + 1)\n    $win32::GetWindowText($hwnd, $sb, $len + 1)\n    Write-Output \"Agent window found: $($sb.ToString()) (HWND: $($hwnd.ToString()))\"\n} else {\n    Write-Output \"Agent window NOT found, need to start it\"\n    \n    # Start cursor agent in a new window\n    $proc = Start-Process -PassThru -FilePath \"cmd.exe\" -ArgumentList \"/k cursor agent\" -WindowStyle Normal\n    Write-Output \"Started cursor agent (PID: $($proc.Id))\"\n    Start-Sleep -Seconds 3\n    \n    # Try to find it again\n    $hwnd2 = $win32::FindWindow($null, \"● agent - Cursor\")\n    if ($hwnd2 -ne [IntPtr]::Zero) {\n        $len2 = $win32::GetWindowTextLength($hwnd2)\n        $sb2 = New-Object System.Text.StringBuilder ($len2 + 1)\n        $win32::GetWindowText($hwnd2, $sb2, $len2 + 1)\n        Write-Output \"Agent window found after start: $($sb2.ToString()) (HWND: $($hwnd2.ToString()))\"\n    } else {\n        Write-Output \"Still couldn't find agent window\"\n    }\n}","timeout":15}}],"api":"openai-completions","provider":"deepseek","mo