{"type":"custom_message","customType":"openclaw.runtime-context","content":"Conversation info (untrusted metadata):\n```json\n{\n  \"chat_id\": \"user:ou_6509d346e8d50ef882f89c436e6c977f\",\n  \"message_id\": \"om_x100b6dcee0a4eca8b03e32a63ba556b\",\n  \"sender_id\": \"ou_6509d346e8d50ef882f89c436e6c977f\",\n  \"sender\": \"Yousan(叶枝君)\",\n  \"timestamp\": \"Mon 2026-06-15 15:33 GMT+8\"\n}\n```\n\nSender (untrusted metadata):\n```json\n{\n  \"label\": \"Yousan(叶枝君) (ou_6509d346e8d50ef882f89c436e6c977f)\",\n  \"id\": \"ou_6509d346e8d50ef882f89c436e6c977f\",\n  \"name\": \"Yousan(叶枝君)\"\n}\n```","display":false,"details":{"source":"openclaw-runtime-context"},"id":"0b1b4862","parentId":"fee65b2b","timestamp":"2026-06-15T07:34:03.483Z"}
{"type":"message","id":"40187f6a","parentId":"0b1b4862","timestamp":"2026-06-15T07:34:20.714Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"The user chose option 3 - writing a Cursor extension (VS Code extension) that listens for instructions and injects them into Cursor's agent.\n\nA VS Code extension for Cursor that:\n1. Runs a local WebSocket server\n2. Listens for incoming instructions from OpenClaw\n3. Automatically opens the Cursor Agent panel\n4. Injects the instruction text\n5. Triggers execution\n\nLet me plan the extension structure:\n\n```\ncursor-bridge-extension/\n├── package.json           # Extension manifest\n├── src/\n│   ├── extension.ts       # Extension entry point\n│   └── bridge.ts          # WebSocket server + agent integration\n└── .vscodeignore\n```\n\nHowever, VS Code extensions are typically written in TypeScript. The extension needs to:\n1. Register as a VS Code extension\n2. Start a WebSocket server on a local port\n3. When a message arrives via WebSocket, use the VS Code API to:\n   - Open the chat/agent panel\n   - Set the input text\n   - Trigger execution\n\nFor Cursor-specific APIs, I need to check what's available. In standard VS Code:\n- `vscode.commands.executeCommand('workbench.action.chat.open')` - Opens chat\n- For setting text and sending, it's more complex\n\nIn Cursor, the agent is accessible via:\n- `cursor.composerChatService` or similar (internal API)\n- Or via the `workbench.action.chat.open` command\n\nActually, let me think about this more practically. A VS Code extension can:\n1. Use `vscode.commands.executeCommand()` to trigger built-in actions\n2. Use the `window.createWebviewPanel()` for custom UI\n3. Use clipboard API or the `env.clipboard` API\n\nFor Cursor-specific actions, I might need to look at what commands are available when Cursor is running. The extension can:\n\n1. Start a WebSocket server in the extension's `activate()` hook\n2. When a message arrives:\n   - Use `vscode.commands.executeCommand()` to open Cursor's agent\n   - Use `vscode.env.clipboard.writeText()` to set the instruction\n   - Simulate paste + enter via command execution\n\nBut for actually setting text in the agent chat input and triggering execution, I need to find the right commands.\n\nLet me check what commands are available in Cursor by querying the running instance. Actually, I can try to list commands from the IPC channel.\n\nAlternatively, I can take a simpler approach:\n1. The extension opens a WebSocket server\n2. When it receives an instruction, it:\n   a. Copies the text to clipboard\n   b. Opens the Cursor agent panel\n   c. Executes paste (Ctrl+V)\n   d. Sends the message (Enter)\n\nAll of these can be done through VS Code extension commands!\n\nIn VS Code:\n- `workbench.action.chat.open` - Opens chat\n- `editor.action.clipboardPasteAction` - Pastes\n- There's no direct \"Send\" command, but I could use:\n  - Clipboard API + opening terminal and running commands\n  - Or simulate the send action\n\nActually, for Cursor specifically, the agent might have different commands. Let me check what Cursor exposes.\n\nHmm, I don't know the exact Cursor command IDs. But I can take a practical approach:\n\nThe extension can:\n1. Listen on a WebSocket\n2. Write pending tasks to a file the extension watches\n3. Use the VS Code `window.terminals` API or clipboard approach\n\nLet me take the most practical approach:\n\n**Extension behavior:**\n1. On activate: start a WebSocket server on port 18792\n2. When a message arrives:\n   - Write it to a temp file\n   - Execute `cursor --goto` or similar to open the file with the instruction\n   - OR use clipboard + execute command to open agent\n\nBut actually, the simplest approach that will definitely work:\n\nThe extension:\n1. Registers a command `cursor-bridge.sendInstruction` that takes a string parameter\n2. The command opens the agent panel, sets the input, and sends it\n3. For receiving from OpenClaw, the extension starts a WebSocket server\n4. When a message arrives, it calls the command\n\nFor the actual agent interaction, I'll try to:\n1. Use `vscode.commands.executeCommand('cursor.composerChatInputFocus')` or similar\n2. Use `vscode.commands.executeCommand('cursor.composerChatSend')` or similar\n\nIf those commands don't exist, I'll fall back to clipboard approach.\n\nLet me write the extension. I'll use TypeScript (compiled to JS) and package it as a VSIX.\n\nActually, for simplicity and speed, let me write it in plain JavaScript instead of TypeScript, since we can skip the compilation step. VS Code/Cursor extensions can be written in JavaScript too.\n\nLet me structure it:\n\n```\ncursor-bridge-extension/\n├── package.json\n├── extension.js          # Main extension code\n└── .vscodeignore\n```\n\nWait, for Cursor, I should check the extension directory. Earlier I saw `extensions\\anysphere.remote-ssh-1.1.2` and `extensions\\anysphere.remote-ssh-1.1.3`. So Cursor extensions are stored in `~/.cursor/extensions/`.\n\nBut for development, I should create it in a different location and have Cursor load it from there.\n\nLet me write the extension:\n\n```json\n{\n  \"name\": \"cursor-bridge\",\n  \"displayName\": \"Cursor Bridge\",\n  \"version\": \"1.0.0\",\n  \"publisher\": \"openclaw\",\n  \"engines\": { \"vscode\": \"^1.90.0\" },\n  \"activationEvents\": [\"onStartupFinished\"],\n  \"main\": \"./extension.js\",\n  \"contributes\": {\n    \"commands\": [{\n      \"command\": \"cursor-bridge.sendInstruction\",\n      \"title\": \"Send Instruction to Cursor Agent\"\n    }]\n  }\n}\n```\n\nFor the extension code, I need to:\n\n1. Start a WebSocket server\n2. On receive instruction:\n   a. Focus Cursor agent panel\n   b. Set the input text\n   c. Execute/send\n\nThe tricky part is setting the input text and sending. Let me try:\n- `vscode.commands.executeCommand('workbench.action.chat.open')` - to open the panel\n- Then try various commands to set and send text\n\nI can also use the `vscode.window.tabGroups` API to find the agent tab.\n\nActually, let me look at what Cursor-specific commands are available. In the running Cursor instance, I can query commands via WebSocket IPC.\n\nBut for now, let me write the extension and make it work. Even if I have to use clipboard + keyboard shortcuts, it should work.\n\nFor the compiling/packaging, I can just create the extension files in a directory and have Cursor load it.\n\nLet me write the extension now.","thinkingSignature":"reasoning_content"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_00_uy6gcvEBhdqxeemaLlGR2453","name":"update_plan","arguments":{"plan":[{"step":"创建 Cursor Extension 骨架 (package.json + extension.js)","status":"in_progress"},{"step":"编写 WebSocket 服务器 + 自动注入 Agent 指令逻辑","status":"pending"},{"step":"安装到 Cursor 扩展目录","status":"pending"},{"step":"重启 Cursor 并验证","status":"pending"},{"step":"更新 skill 指向新扩展","status":"pending"}]}}],"api":"openai-completions","provider":"deepseek","model":"deepseek-v4-flash","usage":{"input":11575,"output":1651,"cacheRead":212864,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":226090,"cost":{"input":0.0016205000000000002,"output":0.00046228,"cacheRead":0.005960192,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0.008042971999999999}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1781508843483,"responseId":"abb716a5-f5e1-46ba-bec1-13d5e7639328"}}
