{"type":"message","id":"d1e35518","parentId":"09aec1a9","timestamp":"2026-06-15T07:47:03.811Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"The extension host started (PID 9152), but there's no \"bridge\" or \"activated\" log. The `sharedprocess.log` only says \"Getting extensions control\" - it doesn't mention our extension being added.\n\nThis confirms that Cursor's extension loading mechanism doesn't load our custom extension. The `sharedprocess.log` in the previous session showed \"Added extensions to default profile from external source\" but this new session doesn't show that.\n\nLooking at the `renderer.log`, I see:\n- `Started local extension host with pid 9152`\n- But no mention of loading our specific extension\n\nI think the issue might be that Cursor doesn't support loading arbitrary local extensions. The `anysphere.remote-ssh` extension is installed through Cursor's marketplace. Our extension just being in the folder isn't enough.\n\nLet me try one more thing - install the extension \"properly\" using `cursor --install-extension` with the `--force` flag.\n\nActually wait, I already tried that and it said \"already installed\".\n\nYou know what, let me just give up on the extension approach for now and go with the file-based polling approach that the user can use. The extension approach requires deeper Cursor internals knowledge that I don't have.\n\nInstead, let me use the approach that already works:\n1. Write the task to cursor_tasks.json (MCP fallback)\n2. Tell the user what to type in Cursor\n\nAnd let me also check one more thing - maybe the `cursor agent` command works now that Cursor has been restarted and the user is logged in.","thinkingSignature":"reasoning_content"},{"type":"text","text":"扩展确实没被加载，Cursor 可能不加载非官方来源的本地扩展。\n\n目前 **MCP 方案是唯一能用的**。我先发任务过去："},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_00_N2JGeddXLRWS440yqD3R7571","name":"write","arguments":{"content":"{\n  \"taskId\": \"mqf00001\",\n  \"timestamp\": \"2026-06-15T07:4